        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "c88",
      "file": "c88.wav",
      "text": "I am going to walk through my reasoning so you can poke holes in it. We could rebake the primary key, but that touches every row and it is a large table, so the cost is real. The alternative avoids the extra hop entirely, which is why I am leaning that way, but I am not attached to it, and if you see a problem I am missing I would genuinely rather hear it now than after we ship.",
      "source": "human",
      "tags": [
        "long",
        "status"
      ],
      "condition": "noisy",
      "checks": {
        "stt": {
          "biasTerms": [
            "primary key"
          ],
          "tier": "T3"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "c89",
      "file": "c89.wav",
      "text": "Recording for a benchmark is more work than people expect. You read each line exactly as written, save it as its own clip, keep your normal microphone and your normal pace, and then you re-record a handful of them in a slightly noisy room so you have something to measure robustness against. It is an afternoon of talking plus the time to verify every transcript, which is why I am building it up in tiers instead of all at once.",
      "source": "human",
      "tags": [
        "long"
      ],
      "condition": "noisy",
      "checks": {
        "stt": {
          "biasTerms": [],
          "tier": "T3"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "c90",
      "file": "c90.wav",
      "text": "The privacy story is the part I care about most. Speech recognition is always on device, there is no cloud transcription ever, and the only thing that can leave the machine is an optional rewrite that I key myself. Before that call goes out, anything sensitive is tokenized into a nonce, the rewrite happens over the redacted text, and the original is restored locally afterward. There is no telemetry and no analytics, none of it is collected.",
      "source": "human",
      "tags": [
        "long",
        "proj"
      ],
      "condition": "noisy",
      "checks": {
        "stt": {
          "biasTerms": [],
          "tier": "T3"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "c91",
      "file": "c91.wav",
      "text": "Let me give you the full picture in one go, because I keep explaining it in pieces and it comes out scattered. The product is a local first dictation tool for the Mac. You hold a key, you talk, you let go, and the text is inserted into whatever app you are in, all in a single undoable action. Recognition runs entirely on device, so your voice never leaves the machine. There are several engines you can choose from, Parakeet, Whisper, Qwen, Moonshine and a couple of others, and each one supports a dictionary so that when I say FluidAudio or WhisperKit or Kubernetes it comes out spelled correctly instead of as three lowercase words. On top of recognition there is an optional rewrite step that uses a language model, but that is the only thing that ever touches the network, and only after the sensitive parts of the transcript have been swapped out for placeholder tokens. The rewrite happens over that redacted text, the model never sees the real values, and the placeholders are filled back in locally once it returns. If a single placeholder does not come back exactly once, the whole thing falls back to the local transcript and tells me, because a dropped token would either leak something I redacted or corrupt the part I wanted left alone. That gate is a hard check, not a nice to have. The rest is configuration. A mode is just a named bag of settings that a generic pipeline runs, so adding a new one is data, never code, and I can route to different prompts based on a trigger phrase at the end of what I say. It is the kind of thing I would never have finished without leaning hard on the robots, and honestly it is the most fun I have had building something in a long time.",
      "source": "human",
      "tags": [
        "stress",
        "proj"
      ],
